Prediction Problem

My prediction problem is: Can we predict whether a mushroom is edible or poisonous based on its physical characteristics? This is a classification problem. The variable to predict is the mushroomâs edibility status, which can be categorized into two classes: edible (e) or poisonous (p).

Data source

I plan to do my predictive model final project using the Mushroom Classification Dataset from Kaggle 1. This data set was originally contributed the the UCI Machine Learning repository and contains descriptions of hypothetical samples corresponding to 23 species of gilled mushroom. Each species is classified as edible or poisonious.

  • 1Â Kaggle Dataset â Mushroom Classification

    • Why this data

    This dataset will work well to predict if a mushroom is edible or not through a mushroomâs physical characteristics. There are several motivations for pursing this problem in practicality, saftey, and personal curiosity. The ability to accurately predict whether a mushroom is edible or poisonous from easily observable characteristics could be a valuable tool for foragers, mushroom enthusiasts, and researchers. It enhances safety and knowledge in the field of mycology. Further, a reliable predictive model could potentially reduce the risk of mushroom poisoning by providing an additional tool for identifying poisonous varieties, especially with how foraging is becoming popular and mainstream.

    I am personally interested in this since I have little experience with mushrooms in the wild but I enjoy cooking with them a lot. However, I have noticed that out of the thousands and thousands of mushroom species, we only eat around 5 on the daily. While I am not in the foraging community, I have seen posts come up about identifying mushrooms and finding it really interesting how people depend on what they look like to know if they are safe or not. Further, my parents come from China which has a rich history of using mushrooms in traditional medicine which has always made me wonder how people discovered their medicinal properties and how they learned which ones were safe, which ones were deadly, and which ones were medically helpful in specific doses.

    Data quality & complexity check

    This dataset has been consistently used by people to conduct research with and is hosted by reliable sources. This dataset has a wide variety of variables for me to chooose from. There are 23 total variables. There are numerica variables present after reading the overview provided on the website, however, the numeric variables are coded as a factor. Therefore, when running an overview, it shows that there are 23 categorical variables and 0 numeric. This will be addressed and fixed in data cleaning. There are 8125 total observations which makes this a good sized dataset.

    [1] 8124
    [1] 23
    [1] 0

    Despite the size of this dataset, there are no missingness isses.

    Potential data issues

    Looking at the distribution of the data, it is very slightly skewed towards edible (e). Since the data is slightly skewed, I plan to use stratified sampling for this data to make sure the poisonous (p) category is properly represented.
